<HL>
   International:
   Eager Investors
   Flock to Hungary,
   Find Slim Pickings
   ----
   By Philip Revzin
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   BUDAPEST, Hungary -- Budapest's five luxury hotels are
jammed with American, German, British, South Korean,
Austrian, Japanese and French business executives. All are
looking for joint-venture deals or Hungarian companies in
which to invest the $80 million to $100 million entrusted to
them by institutional investors eager to cash in on Eastern
Europe.
   But the pickings are getting slim -- fast. "There are
maybe 50 -- maximum -- state companies capable of absorbing
an investment of $100 million or $150 million," says Daniel
S. Fogel, dean of the International Management Center here.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Two thick books list 67 state companies eager to marry
rich benefactors; most are Stalinian white elephants that
make low-quality, high-cost steel or machine tools. The 4th
of April Machine Factory in Kiskunfelegyhaza makes boilers
and air conditioners and offers a Western partner a
52,000-square-foot workshop and 1,106 employees. The Duna
Shoe Factory needs a few hundred thousand dollars to buy new
stitching and gluing machines; it posted a loss of 80 million
forints ($1.3 million) last year. On the government's list of
its 50 most promising companies is a maker of vacuum tubes,
an item that most of the world long ago replaced with
transistors.
   Investing here requires an on-the-ground presence. Stephen
Frater, chief executive of Cohfin, Italian industrialist
Carlo De Benedetti's new Hungarian investment company, opened
shop Dec. 1 in the Hotel Gellert. He has $50 million he would
like to deploy this year. So far he has signed four letters
of intent with potential partners: a porcelain maker, a
printer, a retail store and a financial-services company.
   "Once you find a company you then have to roll up your
sleeves and slog through a nonsensical set of numbers, then
sit down with your own auditors and reconstruct the balance
sheet," says Mr. Frater. Hungary "is not a place to fly in,
have a round of meetings, fly out and come back when the
papers are ready."
   The problems aren't just bureaucratic. Mr. Frater's phone
rings.
   "Yes, yes. We're ready to close the deal. We're prepared
to put a payment in escrow."
   Pause.
   "Escrow. E-S-C-R-O-W. It means we put the money in a bank
account and he gets it when the deal is done."
   Pause.
   "Oh, come over tomorrow and I'll explain it to you."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900405-0163
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900405-0163.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Raychem Plans
   To Take a Charge
   For Its 3rd Period
   ----
   By Carrie Dolan
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8C
</SO>
<CO>
   RYC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   MENLO PARK, Calif. -- Raychem Corp. said it would take a
charge of up to $90 million in its third quarter, which will
cause a loss for the fiscal year. The charge will cover
severance payments, management consolidations and certain
expenses associated with divestitures.
   Raychem said excluding the one-time charge and taxes,
results in the quarter ended March 31 were at about the
break-even level, reflecting a larger-than-expected drop in
its defense business. Sales were about 5% above the
year-earlier quarter's level of $270 million "in constant
currency," Raychem said. A spokesman said that since about
60% of sales come from international markets, currency
fluctuations could change final sales results.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Raychem makes aerospace, automotive, electronics and
telecommunications products. Its stock closed yesterday at
$27.75, down 25 cents, in composite trading on the New York
Stock Exchange.
   In the year-earlier third quarter, Raychem took a one-time
charge of $10.7 million for certain programs intended to
"improve corporate efficiency." In that quarter, Raychem
posted net income of $2.4 million, or seven cents a share
fully diluted, down 92% from a year earlier.
   Raychem has seen several quarters of declining profits,
which the company has blamed, in part, on losses from its
Raynet unit. That unit, which designs fiber-optics systems,
is still developing products and markets. A spokesman said
Raynet is expected to cost the company about $60 million this
fiscal year, ending June 30. However, Raychem said it
"remains fully committed" to the Raynet unit, where
technology trials now under way are showing "encouraging
results."
   The company will cut its work force by 8%, dismissing 900
workers to reduce staff to about 10,500. Raychem also said it
will consolidate certain management and administrative jobs,
and sell undeveloped land in Menlo Park, Calif. Raychem said
it plans to acquire manufacturing sites in other,
less-expensive parts of the U.S.
   In addition, Raychem plans to sell its Advanced Packaging
Systems division, which makes products to enhance
communications among integrated circuits, and much of its
shape memory alloy business, which makes metals for the
aerospace industry.
   Raychem said the moves are intended to reduce ongoing
expenses but a spokesman wouldn't estimate how much money
will be saved. Raychem said once the moves are implemented,
it expects the costs to be recovered over two to three years.
   For the fiscal year ended June 30, 1989, the company
posted net income of $36.3 million, or $1.02 a fully diluted
share, on sales of $1.08 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900405-0162
