<HL>
   Technology:
   IBM Researchers
   `Write' With Atoms
   On a Metal Surface
   ----
   By Richard L. Hudson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   IBM
</CO>
<IN>
SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Researchers at International Business Machines
Corp. achieved a milestone in ultramicroscopic manufacturing,
by "writing" with individual atoms on a metal surface.
   The researchers used a special IBM-invented microscope to
position individual atoms of xenon gas precisely on a nickel
plate. They arranged the xenon atoms into patterns -- for
instance, tracing out the letters "IBM" in lines one atom
wide.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The technological feat, described in today's issue of
Nature, a weekly British science journal, is the latest of
several recent steps towards the ultimate in
micromanufacturing: precise manipulation of individual atoms
and molecules. Scientists talk of one day being able to make
ultrasmall electronic circuitry, with dimensions of just one
atom or molecule. By comparison, the circuitry in today's
top-performance computer chips is at least 1,000 times more
coarse. In theory, smaller circuitry permits faster, less
expensive and more complex computing.
   But at the moment, such research is more laboratory
curiosity than commercial reality. In their Nature report,
the IBM researchers said use of their technique may be
limited to certain types of atoms and molecules. Also, the
equipment they used is too costly and complex to contemplate
commercial applications anytime soon.
   The technique, developed at IBM's Almaden Research Center
in San Jose, Calif., uses the so-called scanning tunnelling
microscope. The device, for whose invention two IBM
scientists shared a Nobel Prize in 1987, is normally used in
physics and materials laboratories to produce images of
individual atoms and molecules. The microscope has a
single-atom tip that, when energized by a tiny electric
current, can trace the atomic surface contours of many
materials.
   By simply increasing the electric current passing through
the tip, the Almaden researchers converted the device from a
"reader" of atomic structures to a "writer." Specifically,
the researchers scattered xenon atoms at random over a nickel
surface, and then used the microscope's tip to drag each
xenon atom into its desired position on the nickel surface.
The result was uniform lines of closely spaced xenon atoms on
top of the nickel surface.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900405-0154
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900405-0154.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Axel Springer Verlag
   To Expand, Redesign
   Its Medical Tribune
</HL>
<DATE>
04/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   G.SPR
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Axel Springer Verlag AG, hoping to build on
its foothold in U.S. publishing, will introduce today a
redesigned and expanded Medical Tribune, the national
newspaper for physicians.
   The West German publisher bought the Medical Tribune in
August from the family of its founder, the late Arthur
Sackler, for an estimated $80 million. Medical Tribune was
the first acquisition in the U.S. by Axel Springer, one of
the largest newspaper publishers in Europe.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Axel Springer, as of this week's issue, converted the
publication from a tabloid into a broadsheet and expanded its
editorial matter to include life style features as well as
clinical news. Published now every two weeks with editions in
Japan, France, and West Germany, Medical Tribune will become
a weekly in early 1991, said Richard Dauncey, president of
Medical Tribune.
   "We want to bridge the gap between the physicians'
professional and private lives," said Mr. Dauncey. Axel
Springer has spent about $8 million revamping the newspaper,
which has U.S. circulation of about 125,000. "We go from
clinical news to matters of cultural significance."
   In a related development, Axel Springer is expected to
launch more U.S. publications in the medical field. A
consumer magazine called Family Health, now being tested in
the U.K. by Axel Springer, may also be launched in the U.S.
within a year, Mr. Dauncey said.
   Axel Springer is tapping a lucrative advertising market. A
large number of publications vie for about $420 million in
pharmaceutical and medical-related advertising. The
readership is potentially large also, with an estimated
500,000 physicians in the U.S. alone.
   But even Axel Springer executives acknowledge they are
expanding Medical Tribune during a depressed period.
Advertising revenue for pharmaceuticals fell about 30% in the
first quarter, said Mr. Dauncey.
   "The U.S. publication is an important part of our becoming
a world-wide provider of medical news," said Helmut Fluhrer,
Axel Springer project manager for mergers and acquisitions.
News from "the medical industry in the U.S. is vitally
important to other countries," he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
