<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Fed's Arsenal Has Only One Big Gun
</HL>
<DATE>
04/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19
</SO>
<GV>
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   "Fed Has Lost Much of Its Power to Sway U.S. Interest
Rates" reads the headline on your March 12 page-one story.
Truth to tell, the Fed never had much power to sway U.S.
interest rates.
   The Fed can control directly one thing and one thing only:
the amount of high-powered money or the monetary base
(currency plus deposits at Federal Reserve). Changes in the
base in turn affect interest rates, broader monetary
aggregates and, through them, inflation, economic activity
and exchange rates.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   If it chooses to do so, the Fed can use its control over
the base to peg a particular interest rate such as the
federal funds rate. But if it does so, it must accept
whatever happens to other magnitudes affected by the base,
including the level of inflation. That means that, while the
Fed can peg or control the nominal federal funds rate, it
cannot control the real rate (i.e., the nominal rate minus
the rate of inflation). Similarly, it cannot control both the
federal funds rate and the long-term rate.
   Capital markets have long been linked internationally, and
that has tended to make real interest rates in different
countries tend toward roughly the same level. But nominal
rates are a different matter, since they reflect anticipated
movements in exchange rates, which in turn are linked to
anticipated rates of inflation in different countries.
   So long as exchange rates are free to float, the Fed has
as much control over the monetary base as it ever did, and
can, if it wishes, use that control as readily as it ever
could to target any one of a range of nominal magnitudes,
including the federal funds rate and the rate of inflation.
   The inflation of the 1970s did not arise because of the
Fed's impotence, but because it repeatedly chose to use its
control of the monetary base to hold down the federal funds
rate to levels that generated excessive increases in monetary
aggregates. The inevitable result was sky-high interest rates
-- hardly the result the Fed intended. Fortunately, the Fed
has learned from that experience and is not likely to repeat
that mistake.
   Milton Friedman
   Senior Research Fellow
   Hoover Institution
   Stanford, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900405-0128
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900405-0128.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   Seoul Unveils Plan to Stimulate Economy,
   But Trade Friction, Inflation May Result
   ----
   By Damon Darlin
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   SEOUL, South Korea -- The government unveiled yet another
plan to stimulate the Korean economy, but one that analysts
say could boost exports and thereby trigger trade friction
and inflation.
   The government's new team of economic ministers, installed
after a cabinet shake-up late last month, wants South Korea
to once again emphasize exports as an engine for economic
growth. To be sure, the government says it won't revert to an
export-at-any-cost policy.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "There will be no return to the past, overzealous export
drive," Deputy Prime Minister Lee Seung Yun said. Indeed, the
plan is modest: Among other things, the government will
double an existing $1.4 billion fund for long-term,
low-interest loans to stimulate export industries.
   The Japan-like export-growth prescription that was
followed by South Korea in the late 1970s and 1980s produced
a period of rapid growth. But the reformist team of economic
ministers ousted from the cabinet last month had advocated
paying more attention to social inequities that are fueling
discontent. That was unpopular with Korea's big business
conglomerates, and the cabinet shake-up was seen as a way for
the government's ruling party to appease the companies.
   Under the former cabinet's policies, South Korea's trade
surplus fell to $900 million in 1989 from $9 billion the year
before. Exports to the U.S. dropped 4.2% last year.
   But the flagging economy and the new drive to push exports
could exacerbate trade tensions with the U.S. The Korean
government is also trying to limit imports of consumer
products and, because of the tough times, the large companies
that dominate South Korea's economy are less likely to make
concessions to open the country's markets, as the U.S. has
demanded.
   The deputy prime minister also said that the South Korean
currency will "be adjusted to a more realistic level." The
won's exchange rate reflects market forces and can be
adjusted to fit government policy, in this case to promote
exports. Thus analysts expect the won to continue to fall
against the dollar, despite inflation fears. The rate now
stands at about 700 won to the dollar, down from about 670
this past summer.
   With or without the plan, many analysts expect the economy
to get better. Experts say the export-dependent economy
touched bottom recently and will be showing improvement this
summer as export volume resumes growth after a flat 1989.
   Yesterday's announcement blamed the economy's slide on
declining exports, which in turn were blamed on sharp wage
increases and the appreciation of the won. A strengthening
won forces Korean manufacturers to raise prices in the U.S.
or reduce profit margins.
   But many economists blame South Korea's economic problems
on its lack of product innovation more than higher prices
overseas. South Korea's big companies usually tag along after
the Japanese and haven't come up with innovative products.
The new policy mentions this problem, but offers no quick
solutions.
   "Korea has bumped up against its technological limits,"
said Henry Morris, chief representative of Kleinwort Benson
Ltd. in Seoul. "It is a problem that hasn't been seriously
addressed in Korea."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
