<HL>
   House Bill Urges
   A Single Agency
   To Oversee Markets
   ----
   By Kevin G. Salwen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C20
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
COMMODITY FUTURES TRADING COMMISSION (CFT)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Two House members unveiled a bill to merge
stock and futures regulation into a single agency, hoping to
replace what they called "an archaic way of regulating
financial instruments."
   The legislation, introduced by Reps. Dan Glickman (D.,
Kan.) and Dennis Eckart (D., Ohio), is the most sweeping
proposal in the debate over who should supervise financial
futures.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The congressmen said they would need strong Bush
administration support to move this bill through. "This
depends on what the administration decides to do," said Mr.
Glickman, a member of the Agriculture Committee. The Treasury
Department has supported a merger as one of several solutions
to what it calls the "regulatory bifurcation."
   The Commodity Futures Trading Commission currently
monitors financial futures, as well as the rest of the
futures industry. But the structure has come under attack
from within the Bush administration, including the Securities
and Exchange Commission, which regulates the stock and
options markets, for creating stock-market volatility and
hindering enforcement efforts.
   Until now, most discussion about the regulatory split has
focused on moving the monitoring of stock-index futures to
the SEC. Stock-index futures, which are controversial because
they can be used in program-trading strategies, allow
investors to bet on the direction of a basket of stocks
without buying the actual securities.
   The Glickman-Eckart bill would create a single agency,
called the Markets and Trading Commission, that would oversee
most of the U.S. financial markets. The congressmen contend
that merging the agencies could avoid one pitfall that some
have feared, the weakening of the CFTC, which could occur if
oversight of index futures were shifted to the SEC.
   The agency also would control stock margins, which are
currently set by the Federal Reserve Board. Futures margins
would remain in the hands of the commodities exchanges, but a
floor would be set. Margins are the good-faith deposits
required for trades.
   Chicago Board of Trade President Thomas Donovan has called
the merger proposal "worth studying" and said that it's
preferable to giving the SEC regulatory control over index
futures. Chicago Mercantile Exchange officials have echoed
Mr. Donovan's remarks.
   A CFTC spokesman immediately attacked the bill, arguing
that "we fail to see any need for merging the two agencies."
   SEC Chairman Richard Breeden said the agency "wouldn't
oppose the merger approach if that's the way Congress
determines to deal with the problem of split jurisdiction."
But he added that "a merger, while desirable from many
perspectives, isn't absolutely necessary to solve the worst
problems" of the regulatory division.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900405-0102
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900405-0102.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Two Publishers
   Of Cable Magazines
   Plan a Merger
   ----
   By Patrick M. Reilly
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9
</SO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- TVSM Inc., a publisher of cable-television
magazines, said it will merge with Crosby Vandenburgh Group,
also a major publisher of cable magazines.
   The merger of the two closely held companies will create
the country's largest publisher of magazines created
primarily for cable system operators and their subscribers.
As cable's penetration of U.S. television households
continues to grow, the cable magazines will be stiff
competition for established publications, such as News
Corp.'s TV Guide.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Boston-based Crosby Vandenburgh will merge its Cable
Publications Inc. division, which publishes the monthly
publication TV Entertainment, with TVSM, which publishes the
Cable Guide. The combined company will retain the TVSM name
and will continue to be run by Mark Edmiston, chairman of the
three-year-old TVSM.
   Terms of the merger weren't disclosed, but sources close
to the negotiation said investors in Crosby Vandenburgh were
offered stock in TVSM. Not involved in the merger is Custom
Magazines Inc., a division of Crosby Vandenburgh and
publisher of single-sponsor magazines.
   The merger was initiated by Frederick Iseman, a principal
of Hambro International Venture Fund, one of the investors in
Crosby Vandenburgh. "With 12 million circulation this makes
TVSM by far the dominant factor in cable publications," said
Mr. Iseman.
   Eventually it's expected TVSM will combine the two
magazines and publish it as one title on a weekly basis.
Already, TVSM is testing a weekly cable guide called TV Times
in San Diego and Huntington Beach, Calif., that tells
customers only what their cable system offers. TVSM said it
will launch this week a TV Time edition in Phoenix, Ariz. For
now, however, the magazines will be published separately.
   The merger is considered particularly attractive because
it gives TVSM a circulation of 12 million, all of it
unduplicated. Crosby Vandenburgh's TV Entertainment has a
circulation of about 4.5 million and is sent to subscribers
to cable systems owned by Tele-Communications Inc. TVSM's
Cable Guide has a circulation of about 7.5 million spread
among several major cable systems operators.
</TEXT>
