<HL>
   Georgia-Pacific Land Gift
   Is Studied by Grand Jury
</HL>
<DATE>
04/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   GP
</CO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE, REITS, LAND DEVELOPMENT (REL)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   ATLANTA -- A federal grand jury is investigating whether
Georgia-Pacific Corp. inflated for tax purposes the value of
Florida swampland that it donated to a state water management
agency in 1984, a grand jury witness said.
   A spokeswoman for Georgia-Pacific, an Atlanta-based
forest-products concern, declined to comment.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   John Flanagan, deputy assistant executive director of the
Suwannee River Water Management District, in Live Oak, Fla.,
said he and another agency member appeared under subpoena
before a grand jury in Atlanta March 13.
   Mr. Flanagan said Martin Weinstein, an assistant U.S.
attorney, inquired about the circumstances under which
Georgia-Pacific donated 5,400 acres of land to the water
management district, a conservation and management agency, in
1984. He said the grand jury also subpoenaed the agency's
records related to Georgia-Pacific's donation of the Santa Fe
Swamp tract, which is north of Little Santa Fe Lake in
Bradford County.
   Mr. Flanagan said the U.S. attorney is focusing on a $24
million tax deduction that Georgia-Pacific took as a result
of the donation. Georgia-Pacific reportedly purchased the
land in 1981 for $1.9 million. Prosecutors couldn't be
reached for comment.
</TEXT>
